[start section id="20103"]

Ms.  Gentry is a 43-year-old female with a history of metastatic colon cancer with known liver metastasis.  Currently undergoing chemotherapy with FOLFOX plus Avastin.  She returns today for consideration of her fourth cycle of chemotherapy.  Her oncologic history is summarized below as follows:
1. January 2010, patient reports a three- to four-month history of diarrhea.  She was found to be anemic with a hemoglobin of 6.
2. February 3, 2010, colonoscopy shows an enlarged near-obstructing mass in the ascending colon.  Biopsy consistent with invasive moderately differentiated adenocarcinoma.
3. February 8, 2010, CT abdomen and pelvis shows a 7.1- x 7.2- x 9.1-cm mass in the ascending colon.  Multiple low-attenuation liver lesions in both lobes in the caudate lobe are noted as well, largest 3.3 cm.  Single enlarged retroperitoneal lymph node.  Also noted septate and cystic left adnexal mass measuring 5.4 x 4.8 x 6.3 cm.
4. February 12, 2010, due to the near-obstructing nature of her colon mass, patient underwent palliative right hemicolectomy.  Pathology found moderately differentiated invasive grade 3 of 4 adenocarcinoma, mass measuring 9.5 x 8 x 2.8-cm in the ascending colon.  Tumor invades through the muscularis propria into pericolic fat, surgical margins negative.  Twenty-one of 34 lymph nodes positive for metastatic spread.  Bilateral oophorectomy shows benign findings.
5. March 18, 2010, patient began her first cycle of FOLFOX plus Avastin chemotherapy.
6. Patient received cycle three of chemotherapy after initial delay due to neutropenia on the 22nd of April.  She had omission of bolus at that time.
Since Ms. Gentry was treated on the 22nd of April, she notes that she is feeling significantly improved and denies any significant peripheral neuropathy, abdominal pain, shortness-of-breath, or change in bowel habits.  She did have some mild diarrhea, well-controlled with one-to-two Imodium following loose stools.  This only occurred a couple of days after chemotherapy.  She has also had a few nose sores, but no other complaints.  She denies any hand-foot syndrome.  She does have a runny nose for which she takes over-the-counter antihistamines as-needed.  She has not had any epistaxis.  Mrs. Delmonte does note in the last two days she has developed a slight tickle in her throat with mild hoarseness of her voice and some mild pain as well.  She has not had any fevers or chills.  She denies any cough.

[end section id="20103"]

